==English==
{{rfc}}

===Etymology===

Derived from latin ''mater'' and middle english "moder" 

* Mother + ish (suffix)


===Adjective===

# Of or pertaining to [[maternal]] quality;
# Pertaining to affectionate and sensitive character
# Of or pertaining to warm and embonpoint appearance;

===Usage of the term===

* King Solomon identified the real parent by her extremely selfless and motherish act. (folk tale about the wisdom of King Solomon)

* He is very motherish in his dealings with people.

* A young man would surely be attracted to her, she looks petite and charming and also motherish and graceful

* She thinks it is not motherish to send a child to a boarding school 

* The music was too discordant and loud to be motherish as one would expect for a light entertainment.

===Related terms and synonyms===

(warm and embonpoint in appearance):  [[motherly]], [[motherlike]]

(warm and sensitive in approach and character): [[maternal]], [[motherliness]]


